      &Ad.
  Interrupt
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.TIMx wiring diagram
:efig.
:h2.Using Timers for Interrupts
:p.Before we can actually program any of the timers, we have to first 
enable them -- that requires you to set the correct bit in either 
:pk.RCC->APB1ENR1:epk. or :pk.RCC->APB2ENR:epk.. Here is a table of 
what bit name you would set to :pv.1:epv. with the necessary C 
statements listed:
:i2.Enabling (APB1/APB2 register)
:table id=timenb cols='1i 3i'.
:tcap.TIMx Enablement Statements
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Timer:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.C Statement:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM1:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB2ENR |= RCC_APB2ENR_TIM1EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM2:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM2EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM3:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM3EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM6:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM6EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM7:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM7EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM15:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB2ENR |= RCC_APB2ENR_TIM15EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.TIM16:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB2ENR |= RCC_APB2ENR_TIM16EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.LPTIM1:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_LPTIM1EN;:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pv.LPTIM2:epv.
:c.:pk.RCC->APB1ENR2 |= RCC_APB1ENR2_LPTIM2EN;:epk.
:etable.
:note.See :tref refid=timtbl. for the bitness and counting direction 
associated with the timers if you flipped to this table from the ToC or 
index!
:lblbox.What Timers are for What?
:p.Not all the timers are equal! Some of them are generally used for 
different purposes, like so:
:dl.
:dthd.Timer
:ddhd.Usage
:dt.:pv.TIM1:epv. 
:dd.Synchronizing the ADC, interfacing with specific sensors, producing 
multi-phase PWM signals
:dt.:pv.TIM2/3:epv. 
:dd.PWM, high-accuracy interrupts, sampling input clock signals
:dt.:pv.TIM6/7:epv. 
:dd.Low-accuracy interrupts (decade counters, slow interval timers)
:dt.:pv.TIM15:epv. 
:dd.Sampling the PWM of an input signal, high-accuracy interrupts
:dt.:pv.TIM16:epv. 
:dd.High-accuracy interrupts
:dt.:pv.LPTIM1/2:epv. 
:dd.Wakeup timers while the CPU is powered down
:dt.SysTick
:dd.Operating system scheduler jiffy (timeslice) n
:edl.
:p.Note that the :hp2.SysTick:ehp2. timer channel is special -- it is a 
built-in ARM Cortex-M CPU peripheral and not an STM peripheral like all 
of the rest on this list!
:elblbox.
:p.After you enable the timer block in the APB register that 
corresponds to the timer in question, you need to set the 
:hp2.prescaler.:ehp2. There is a formula that is very handy here to 
help you derive the correct (16-bit) prescaler value:
:i2.Setting PSC
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:df align=center.
F sub <CK_CNT> = <F sub <CK_PSC>> over <PSC + 1>
:edf.
:figcap.TIMx->PSC formula
:efig.
:p.Remember, by default, :f.F sub CK_CNT:ef. is 4 MHz! Knowing this, 
you can solve for the prescaler value you want. Since we want to 
trigger :hp5.interrupts,:ehp5. you need to also set the :hp2.autoreload 
register.:ehp2. The formula to calculate this depends on the previous 
formula's output value, and is as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:df align=center.
T sub out = <(ARR + 1) * (PSC + 1)> over <F sub CK_PSC>
= <(ARR + 1)> over <F sub CK_CNT>
:edf.
:figcap.TIMx->PSC formula
:efig.
:note.You will likely want to use the :hp1.second:ehp1. equated 
function (the right-most one), because you can omit the prescaler for 
faster clocks (which will be useful when you do :hp2.PWM:ehp2.).
:h3.Enabling the Timer
:p.To actually enable your timer, you would simply use one of the lines 
from :tref refid=timenb. like so (for TIM6), and also set 
:pk.TIMx->PSC:epk. alongside :pk.TIMx->ARR:epk.:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void timersetup() {
    RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM6EN;
    TIM6->ARR = 3972;           // this is for a 1-second period
    TIM6->PSC = 995;
    TIM6->CR1 |= TIM6_CR1_CEN;  // enable counting
}
:exmp.
:figcap.TIM6 initialization sample
:efig.
:h3.Enabling Interrupts
:p.At this point, TIM6 is active and counting... but it is 
:hp2.not:ehp2. generating interrupts! To achieve this, there is a bit 
we need to set in the :pk.TIM(6,7)->DIER:epk. 
:fn.DMA/Interrupt Enable Register
:efn.
register:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
/* TIM6 */
TIM6->DIER |= TIM_DIER_UIE;
NVIC_EnableIRQ(TIM6_IRQn);
NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(TIM6_IRQn);
:exmp.
 
:figcap.TIM6 interrupt enablement example
:efig.
:h3.Timer ISR
:p.Last but not least, we need to write an :hp2.ISR:ehp2. 
:fn.Interrupt Service Routine
:efn.
for our TIM6 IRQ that we are now generating:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void TIM6_IRQHandler() {
    // do something here...
    TIM6->SR &= ~TIM_SR_UIF;            // silence interrupt flag
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(TIM6_IRQn);    // dismiss interrupt
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.TIM6 interrupt enablement example
:efig.
:p.This function needs to be named specifically for the timer; if you 
were using TIM2, you would define the function as 
:pv.TIM2_IRQHandler:epv.! Likewise, this function does :hp1.two:ehp1. 
key things:
:ol.
:li.Dismiss the interrupt flag within the timer's :hp2.status register:ehp2.
:li.Dismiss the interrupt (or, more accurately, inform that processing 
of the ISR is complete) on the NVIC
:eol.
:lblbox.Taking Too Long!
:p.Something very important that some students will not take into 
account (especially on their final projects) is that any code within a 
timer ISR needs to :hp1.finish before the timer fires again!:ehp1. If 
you have a timer that triggers every 10 milliseconds, the code 
contained within that ISR's function body has to finish within 10 
milliseconds; failure to do this will result in the CPU being stuck 
processing the timer ISR forever!
:elblbox.
:h2 id=pwm.Using Timers for PWM
:p.:hp2.Pulse-width modulation:ehp2. is a trick wherein you vary the 
:hp5.duty cycle:ehp5. of a square wave to achieve various analog 
voltages. This can prove extremely useful for some control systems, 
including:
:ul.
:li.Motor speed
:li.LED brightness
:eul.
:p.PWM works by :hp1.subdividing the output voltage of a digital I/O 
pin:ehp1. by some percentage (the aforementioned duty cycle). PWM 
looks, practically, like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
50% duty cycle:
 
     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.
     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.
&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.     &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.     &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.     &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.
 
25% duty cycle:
 
     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.        &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.        &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
     &Lv.  &Lv.        &Lv.  &Lv.        &Lv.  &Lv.
     &Lv.  &Lv.        &Lv.  &Lv.        &Lv.  &Lv.
&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.  &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.  &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.  &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.PWM duty cycles
:efig.
:note.100% duty cycle would be flat DC, and 0% duty cycle would be no 
signal at all!
:p.The :hp2.period:ehp2. corresponds to the :hp5.width of the 
pulse:ehp5. and is not the same as the duty cycle. Here is the period 
and the duty cycle of a square wave:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.     &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.
     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.     &Lv.
&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.     &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.     &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.     &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.
     &Lv.&Al.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ar.&Lv. Period - controlled by ARR
     &Lv.&Al.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ar.&Lv. Duty Cycle - controlled by CCR1
 
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.PWM period versus duty cycle
:efig.
:p.So, how does the output voltage derived from our PWM wave actually 
correlate to the duty cycle? Well, examine the handy input chart that 
follows. This is the :hp2.average voltage:ehp2. of the PWM waveform!
:note.The STM32 I/O pins have a logic :pk.1:epk. of :hp5.3.3 
volts:ehp5., so 100% duty cycle corresponds to exactly that.
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:artwork name=pwmvals.
:figcap.PWM and duty cycle relation plot
:efig.
:h3.Selecting a Timer
:p.First and foremost, :hp5.not all timers can be used for PWM!:ehp5. 
See the table :tref refid=timtbl. and note that :hp2.channel:ehp2. 
column -- if a timer has zero channels (like :pv.TIM6:epv. and 
:pv.TIM7:epv.), it :hp1.cannot:ehp1. be used for PWM! Likewise, we will 
demonstrate with :pv.TIM2:epv. (which can drive more than one PWM 
output at a time, but we will just be using one).
:p.For our example, we will use :pv.TIM2:epv., since it can output 
directly from the timer.
:h3 id=timpwm.Differences From the Basic Timers
:p.Unlike the basic timers (:pv.TIM6/7:epv., flip back to 
:hdref refid=timers. for information on those if you flipped here just 
for PWM), the PWM-capable timers require additional setup:
:ol.
:li.Enable the timer with the :pv.RCC->APB1ENR1:epv. register (see 
:tref refid=timenb. for the C statement to do this for :pv.TIM2:epv. or 
whichever timer you're using)
:li.Set the :pk.ARR:epk. and :pk.PSC:epk. registers to select the 
correct PWM frequency
:fn.Remember, the frequency will remain :hp5.constant:ehp5. :hp1.no 
matter what the duty cycle is!:ehp1. 
:efn.
:li.Enable the output channel with the :pk.CCMR1:epk. register
:li.Turn on the output for channel 1 with the :pk.CCER:epk. register
:li.Set the counter threshold value (equivalent to the :hp2.duty 
cycle:ehp2.) in the :pk.CCR1:epk. register
:li.Enable the interrupt by setting the :pv.URS:epv. flag in the 
:pk.CR1:epk. register
:li.Zero the counter by setting the :pv.UG:epv. flag in the 
:pk.EGR:epk. register
:li.Set both the :pv.CC1IE:epv. (channel 1 interrupt enable) and 
:pv.UIE:epv. flags in the :pk.DIER:epk. register
:li.Clear the :pv.CC1IF:epv. and :pv.UIF:epv. flags in the :pk.SR:epk. 
register
:li.Set the :pv.CEN:epv. flag of the :pk.CR1:epk. register to start 
counting
:eol.
:note.This list of tasks also enables :hp5.interrupts:ehp5. on 
:pv.TIM2:epv.; a version of code that won't enable interrupts will also 
be shown later!
:h3.CCR1 and the Duty Cycle
:p.The :pk.TIMx->CCR1:epk. register sets the :hp5.threshold:ehp5. that 
:pk.TIMx->CNT:epk. count-up register must reach before an :q.event:eq. 
occurs -- in our case, the event will:
:ol.
:li.Generate an interrupt
:li.Flip the output state of the PWM bit
:eol.
:p.Remember that the value you write to :pk.CCR1:epk. needs to be a 
:hp1.fraction:ehp1. of the value stored in :pk.ARR:epk.; the value in 
:pk.PSC:epk. is not considered and merely serves to alter the PWM 
frequency. A handy formula for computing the value is as follows:
:df align=center.
CCR1 = DC * ARR
:edf.
:p.Note that :f.DC:ef. is the duty cycle as a decimated percentage.  If 
you have a duty cycle number, like 1 through 10,
:fn.Where 1 is 10% and 10 is 100%
:efn.
you can use this formula instead:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:df align=center.
CCR1 = <DC * ARR> over 10
:edf.
:p.The corresponding C statement would be:
:xmp.TIM2->CCR1 = (dutycycle * TIM2->ARR) / 10;
:exmp.
:figcap.CCR1 duty cycle formula
:efig.
:note.This does :hp1.integer division:ehp1. since we are not using any 
decimated numbers in either the numerator or denominator.
:h3.Picking the Output (or Input)
:p.The most difficult thing to do in this process is configuring the 
:pk.CCMR1:epk. register; the other register configurations are 
relatively simple and self-explained by the list under 
:hdref refid=timpwm.. However, this register is quite tough because it 
has :hp1.two:ehp1. modes, depending on whether or not the timer's 
channel is declared as :hp1.input capture mode:ehp1. 
:fn.This is the mode where you are counting based on pulses appearing 
on a GPIO pin.
:efn.
or :hp1.output compare mode.:ehp1. 
:fn.This is the mode where you are toggling a GPIO pin based on the 
result of a comparison operation performed against the counted value 
(with the counter being fed from a clock).
:efn.
:p.Depending on whether or not one of the channels is declared as an 
input or output, the layout of the register will :hp1.partially:ehp1. 
change. Here is the layout of the register for both input and output 
mode; we will then explore what these do:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
  7   6   5   4   3   2   1   0
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv.1F             &Lv.1PSC   &Lv.CC1S   &Lv.   Prefixed by "IC"
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. d &Lv. c &Lv. b &Lv. a &Lv. b &Lv. a &Lv. b &Lv. a &Lv.   Input Mode
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
 
 
  7   6   5   4   3   2   1   0
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv.1CE&Lv.1M         &Lv.1PE&Lv.1FE&Lv.CC1S   &Lv.   Prefixed by "OC"
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. a &Lv. c &Lv. b &Lv. a &Lv. a &Lv. a &Lv. b &Lv. a &Lv.   Output Mode
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.TIM2_CCMR1 input/output mode layout
:efig.
:p.So, as you can see, :pk.CC1S:epk. is constant between the two 
registers, and, while the register loops again for :pk.CC2S:epk. (see 
the manual for the STM32 you are using; head to :hdref refid=biblio. 
for the programming manual for your STM32), the mode selection 
double-bit will flip the rest of the register
:fn.Well, up until the second :pk.CC2S:epk. register appears!
:efn.
into its :q.alternate personality:eq. depending on what :pk.CC1S:epk. 
is set to:
:dl tsize=15.
:dthd.CC1S
:ddhd.Mode
:dt.:pk.00:epk. 
:dd.:pv.CC1:epv. is declared as an output
:dt.:pk.01:epk. 
:dd.:pv.CC1:epv. is connected to the :pk.TIM2_CH1:epk. GPIO alternate 
function
:dt.:pk.10:epk. 
:dd.:pv.CC1:epv. is connected to the :pk.TIM2_CH2:epk. GPIO alternate 
function
:dt.:pk.10:epk. 
:dd.:pv.CC1:epv. is connected to an internal trigger (this is not 
particularly useful)
:edl.
:p.Whenever you are in output mode, you will need to populate the 
:pk.OC1M:epk. bits (which are bits 4 through 6) to some specific 
pattern; for input mode, you will need to optionally set its prescaler 
(which is similar to the :pk.TIMx->PSC:epk. register, but another 
:q.layer:eq.), set the :hp1.filter:ehp1. (:pk.IC1F:epk.) to control how 
often sampling occurs given several clock pulses, and then start 
counting!
:h4 id=pwmin.Input Setup
:p.Setting up the input is relatively trivial; you only need to use 
code like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM2EN;     // turn on TIM2 power
RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_GPIOAEN;    // turn on GPIO PAx
 
// set PA0 to AF1 (TIM2_CH1)
GPIOA->MODER &= &tilde.0b11;
GPIOA->MODER |= 0b10;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.0b1111;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= 0b0001;
 
// set the prescaler and autoreload register
TIM2->ARR = 0xFFFFFFFF;                   // maximum count value
TIM2->PSC = 0;                            // don't prescale
 
// put channel 1 into input mode and set it to input channel 1
TIM2->CCMR1 &= &tilde.TIM_CCMR1_CC1S;
TIM2->CCMR1 |= 0b01;                      // CC1S = input CH1
 
// count on the rising edge
TIM2->CCER &= &tilde.TIM_CCER_CC1P;
 
// turn on TIM2_IRQHandler() ISR interrupt generation
TIM2->DIER |= TIM_DIER_CC1IE;
NVIC_EnableIRQ(TIM2_IRQn);
 
// start counting
TIM2->CR1 |= TIM_CR1_CEN;
:exmp.
 
:figcap.TIM2 input setup with interrupt
:efig.
:h4.Output Setup
:p.While input mode is much easier to set up, output mode is something 
you need to master for 3040/3050 class!
:p.Output mode requires you to enter a specific bitmask into bits 4 
through 6 of :pk.TIM2->CCMR1:epk.. The bitmasks are as follows:
:table cols='1i *'.
:tcap.TIM2_CCMR1_OC1M Output Modes
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Bitmask:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Description:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.000:epk.
:c.Frozen; no events (interrupts or PWM pin flips) occur
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.001:epk.
:c.Turn on channel 1 when :pk.TIM2->CNT:epk. equals
:pk.TIM2->CCR1:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.010:epk.
:c.Turn off channel 1 when :pk.TIM2->CNT:epk. equals
:pk.TIM2->CCR1:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.011:epk.
:c.Toggle channel 1 when :pk.TIM2->CNT:epk. equals
:pk.TIM2->CCR1:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.100:epk.
:c.Keep channel 1 off
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.101:epk.
:c.Keep channel 1 on
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.110:epk.
:c.PWM mode 1; cause channel 1 to output as long as
:pk.TIM2->CNT:epk. is less than :pk.TIM2->CCR1:epk. (and
keep it from outputting when the reverse condition is true)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.111:epk.
:c.PWM mode 2; cause channel 1 to not output as long as
:pk.TIM2->CNT:epk. is less than :pk.TIM2->CCR1:epk. (and
output when the reverse condition is true)
:etable.
:p.For our PWM output, we want to set :pk.OC1M:epk. to :pk.110:epk. 
(or, :pk.TIM2->CCMR1:epk. should be set to :pk.01100000:epk.).
:note.For the :pk.ARR:epk. value, it needs to be set to whatever your 
desired count is :hp1.minus one.:ehp1. This is because the  register 
starts at 0!
:p.The following code block implements all of the requirements found in 
the list under :hdref refid=timpwm. in output mode:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM2EN;     // turn on TIM2 power
RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_GPIOAEN;    // turn on GPIO PAx
 
TIM2->ARR = 1000;                         // random values...
TIM2->PSC = 2;
 
// set PA0 to AF1 (TIM2_CH1)
GPIOA->MODER &= &tilde.0b11;
GPIOA->MODER |= 0b10;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.0b1111;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= 0b0001;
 
// put channel 1 into output mode
TIM2->CCMR1 &= &tilde.TIM_CCMR1_CC1S;     // CC1S = output
 
// turn on preload mode on channel 1
TIM2->CCMR1 |= TIM_CCMR1_OC1PE;
 
// count on the rising edge
TIM2->CCER &= &tilde.TIM_CCER_CC1P;
 
// assign channel 0 as the output sink and use PWM mode 1
TIM2->CCMR1 |= 0b01100000;
 
// start counting
TIM2->CR1 |= TIM_CR1_CEN;
:exmp.
 
:figcap.TIM2 output setup
:efig.
:p.You can also write a version that generates interrupts:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_TIM2EN;     // turn on TIM2 power
RCC->APB1ENR1 |= RCC_APB1ENR1_GPIOAEN;    // turn on GPIO PAx
 
TIM2->ARR = 1000;                         // random values...
TIM2->PSC = 2;
 
// set PA0 to AF1 (TIM2_CH1)
GPIOA->MODER &= &tilde.0b11;
GPIOA->MODER |= 0b10;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.0b1111;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= 0b0001;
 
// put channel 1 into output mode
TIM2->CCMR1 &= &tilde.TIM_CCMR1_CC1S;     // CC1S = output
 
// turn on preload mode on channel 1
TIM2->CCMR1 |= TIM_CCMR1_OC1PE;
 
// count on the rising edge
TIM2->CCER &= &tilde.TIM_CCER_CC1P;
 
// assign channel 0 as the output sink and use PWM mode 1
TIM2->CCMR1 |= 0b01100000;
 
// only make interrupts when the counter reaches its threshold
TIM2->CR1 |= TIM_CR1_URS;
 
// clear the counter in case it counted a bit
TIM2->EGR |= TIM_EGR_UG;
 
// assign the interrupt to channel 1 and enable interrupts
TIM2->DIER |= (TIM_DIER_CC1IE | TIM_DIER_UIE);
NVIC_EnableIRQ(TIM2_IRQn);
NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(TIM2_IRQn);
 
// flush the interrupt flags
TIM2->SR &= ~(TIM_SR_CC1IF | TIM_SR_UIF);
 
// start counting
TIM2->CR1 |= TIM_CR1_CEN;
:exmp.
 
:figcap.TIM2 output setup with interrupts
:efig.
:h3.IRQ Handler
:p.If you enabled interrupts at all by using any of the above code, you 
will need to write an IRQ handler that looks like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void TIM2_IRQHandler() {
    // do something here...
    TIM2->SR &= &tilde.TIM_SR_UIF;
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(TIM2_IRQn);
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.TIM2 IRQ handler code
:efig.
:h3 id=cpirq.About ClearPendingIRQ
:p.Whenever the ISR starts, the NVIC pending-interrupt bit will be 
cleared automatically. The reason the example ISRs above run 
:pk.NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ:epk. is because if for whatever reason an 
interrupt fires :hp1.during the ISR,:ehp1. you will have nested 
interrupts and you should dismiss the extra interrupts! 
:p.This is especially the case for timers, wherein if your timer ISR 
takes too long to run,
:fn.That is, if your code takes longer to run than your timer interrupt 
frequency!
:efn.
you may end up with a condition where you have far too many nested 
interrupts processing (and this leads to your program crashing).
:h1 id=adc.ADC
:p.Sometimes, you may wish to sample some kind of analog signal in real 
time. Some of these signals may include:
:ul.
:li.The speed of a motor
:li.The voltage of a battery or solar cell
:li.An audio or radio signal
:li.An analog sensor signal like a light sensor's output
:eul.
:p.This is what you would use an :hp2.analog-to-digital converter:ehp2. 
:i1.ADC
:h2.Understanding ADC Sampling
:p.The ADC functional block will take an input signal, sample it at 
specific times, and then quantize it to specific numeric values.
Generally speaking, there are two key parameters for a ADC:
:i2.Resolution (bit depth)
:ol.
:li.The :hp1.sampling rate:ehp1.
:li.The :hp1.bit depth:ehp1. 
:fn.The STM32 ADCs have a :hp2.12-bit:ehp2. depth by default, such that 
it can read values from 0 to 3.3 volts... corresponding to values from 
0 to 4095!
:efn.
-- also called the :hp2.resolution:ehp2. 
:eol.
:h3.Bit Depth
:p.The process of :hp1.quantization:ehp1. is technically 
:hp5.lossy:ehp5., and the following function describes the minimal 
distance in voltage between each possible ADC-reported value given an 
:hp1.n:ehp1.-bit ADC:
:i2.Quantization
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:df align=center.
V sub ref * <1 over <2 sup n>>
:edf.
 
:figcap.ADC quantization round-off voltage/step size
:efig.
:p.Knowing this, it may be helpful to see a chart showing a plot of a 
sine-wave function centered at 0 volts
:fn.Note something very important here: you would have to use 
:hp1.differential mode:ehp1. to sample this signal properly on the 
STM32; you would use :hp1.single-ended mode:ehp1. and add a DC bias to 
sample this when not using differential mode!
:efn.
and its corresponding sample value (given a 12-bit ADC):
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules id=adcpic.
:artwork name=adcsin align=center.
:artwork name=adcsint align=center.
 
:figcap.ADC input function and output value relation
:efig.
:h3.Sampling Rate
:p.The sampling rate, :f.F:ef., of which the sampling period is :f.T = 
1 / F:ef., needs to be :hp5.double:ehp5. the maximum frequency you wish 
to sample -- this is the :hp2.Nyquist rate.:ehp2. Various digital audio 
systems over the years have used the following sample rates:
:ul.
:li.DVD and Blu-Ray audio tracks use 48 KHz
:li.Compact Discs use 44.1 KHz
:li.Digital telephone switches use 8 KHz
:eul.
:p.Likewise, various bit depths have been used in these systems (an 
earlier footnote notes that our STM32 has a 12-bit ADC depth):
:ul.
:li.DVD and Blu-Ray audio tracks use 16, 20, or 24-bit values
:li.CDs use signed 16-bit values
:li.Digital telephone switches use unsigned 8-bit values
:eul.
:h3.Our ADC Parameters
:p.Our STM32's ADC will use the following parameters, all of which can 
be changed (which we will explore next):
:dl tsize=15.
:dthd.Parameter
:ddhd.Value
:dt.Input Range
:dd.0 to 3.3 volts
:dt.Resolution
:dd.12 bits
:dt.Sample Rate
:dd.2.5 clock cycles, derived from SYSCLK
:fn.Remember, you learned about setting the SYSCLK input back in 
:hdref refid=clock.!
:efn.
:edl.
:h2.ADC Settings
:p.The STM32 ADC module is much more complicated than the timer 
modules. Not only can the ADC use :hp1.DMA:ehp1. to drop the sampled 
ADC value in lieu of dropping it into the ADC data register, it also 
has several :hp2.conversion modes!:ehp2. These are as follows:
:i2.Conversion mode
:ul.
:li.:hp2.Single,:ehp2. wherein you manually trigger the ADC to sample 
the inputs into one or more channels
:li.:hp2.Continuous,:ehp2. wherein the ADC will sample one or more 
channels over and over
:li.:hp2.Injected channel mode,:ehp2. wherein the ADC will run in 
continuous mode but will sample extra channels if certain external 
events occur
:eul.
:p.Likewise, there are two ways the ADC can return the captured values 
to your program:
:ul.
:li.When :hp2.DMA mode:ehp2. is enabled, each of the sampled ADC 
channels (which can be one or more) will be copied into your program's 
memory while the CPU is stalled
:fn.The DMA controller needs access to the CPU's main bus, so the CPU 
has to stall and yield control of the bus to the DMA controller 
temporarily; even then, this stalling action still results in faster 
memory copies than if the CPU were doing them in software!
:efn.
into an array of one or more channel values
:li.When DMA mode is disabled, each channel will be written 
back-to-back to the ADC data register, :pk.ADC_DR:epk..
:eul.
:lblbox.Multiple ADC Channels and No DMA
:p.If you are sampling multiple channels, you really are supposed to 
use DMA! The ADC DMA functions will output the 12-bit sampled values 
for each ADC channel into one or more 16-bit (:pv.unsigned short:epv. 
or :pv.uint16_t:epv.) variables in an array.
:p.Without DMA, each of the input channels will be sampled 
(:q.converted:eq.) and deposited into the same data register, 
back-to-back, and with such speed that it is effectively impossible to 
select any specific one value!
:p.Really, what DMA mode does is tell the DMA controller to copy out 
the value from the data register just before it is overwritten with the 
next inputted value.
:elblbox.
:h3 id=adcstp.Configuration Steps
:p.In order to actually configure an ADC, you would complete the 
following tasks:
:ol.
:li.Check the datasheet for your microcontroller to determine which 
GPIO pin corresponds to the input of each ADC's channel
:li.Set the GPIO pin(s) you wish to use for the input(s) to analog 
mode, which is :pk.11:epk. on the :pk.MODER:epk. bitmask
:li.Enable the ADCs by setting the :pk.RCC_AHB2ENR_ADCEN:epk. bit of 
the :pk.RCC->AHB2ENR:epk. register
:li.Clear the :pk.ADC_CR_DEEPPWD:epk. bit of the :pk.ADCx->CR:epk. 
register to turn off ADC deep power-down mode
:li.Wait a short while for the ADC to :q.wake up:eq. 
:fn.You certainly want to wait for the ADC to wake up; writing the 
other bits will :q.fall upon deaf ears:eq. when the ADC block is 
powered down!
:efn.
:li.Set the :pk.ADC_CR_ADVREGEN:epk. bit of the :pk.ADCx_CR:epk. 
register to turn on the voltage regulator (used to provide an accurate 
voltage reference for the sampling)
:li.Wait the same amount of time as before for the regulator to turn on
:li.Select the sampling mode by either setting (enabling) or clearing 
(disabling) the :pk.ADC_CFGR_CONT:epk. bit of the :pk.ADCx->CFGR:epk. 
register
:li.Select the overrun mode to either preserve the last good value or 
permit the ADC to read anyways by setting or clearing the 
:pk.ADC_CFGR_OVRMOD:epk. bit of the :pk.ADCx->CFGR:epk. register
:li.Set the :pk.RES&lbrk.1:0&rbrk.:epk. bits of the :pk.ADCx->CFGR:epk. 
register
:fn.These are bits 4 and 3 of the register!
:efn.
to one of the four values below:
:dl.
:dthd.Value
:ddhd.Resolution Bits
:dt.:pk.00:epk. 
:dd.12 bits
:dt.:pk.01:epk. 
:dd.10 bits
:dt.:pk.10:epk. 
:dd.8 bits
:dt.:pk.11:epk. 
:dd.6 bits
:edl.
:li.If using :hp2.DMA mode:ehp2., set the :pk.ADC_CFGR_DMACFG:epk. and 
:pk.ADC_CFGR_DMAEN:epk. bits of the :pk.ADCx->CFGR:epk. register 
:hp1.and also:ehp1. configure the DMA block
:fn.We will cover this later, flip to :hdref refid=adcdma.if you're 
curious right now!
:efn.
:li.Set the various parameters for the :q.regular sequences:eq. in the 
:pk.ADCx_SQRy:epk. registers where y is 0 to 3; set the :pk.SQ1:epk. to 
:pk.SQ4:epk. bits; read on to see what the layout of this register is 
and what the bit-setting does/selects
:li.Set the :pk.ADC_CR_ADEN:epk. bit of the :pk.ADCx_CR:epk. register
:li.Wait for the :pk.ADC_ISR_ADRDY:epk. bit of the :pk.ADCx->ISR:epk. 
register to set
:fn.C statement to do this: :pv.while(!(ADC1->ISR & 
ADC_ISR_ADRDY));:epv. 
:efn.
:li.Start conversion by setting the :pk.ADC_CR_ADSTART:epk. bit of the 
:pk.ADCx->CR:epk. register
:eol.
:h2.Programming the ADC
:p.This section will show you how to initialize the ADC and show you 
what the register layouts are. At the end, we will examine code samples 
that will do and don't use DMA mode!
:h3.ADC Input Channels
:p.Each ADC has :hp3.18:ehp3. input channels; the ones for 
:pk.ADC1:epk. are as follows for the NUCLEO-32 board:
:fn.For other STM32 boards, see the datasheets listed in 
:hdref refid=biblio.!
:efn.
:table cols='1i 3i'.
:tcap.ADC1 Inputs (STM32L432KCU)
:thd.
:c.Input
:c.GPIO Pin
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.0
:c.Connected to the ADC voltage regulator
:row split=yes.
:c.1
:c.:hp1.Unavailable:ehp1.
:row split=yes.
:c.2
:c.:hp1.Unavailable:ehp1.
:row split=yes.
:c.3
:c.:hp1.Unavailable:ehp1.
:row split=yes.
:c.4
:c.:hp1.Unavailable:ehp1.
:row split=yes.
:c.5
:c.PA0
:row split=yes.
:c.6
:c.PA1
:row split=yes.
:c.7
:c.PA2
:row split=yes.
