:figcap.ADCx_SQR1 layout
:efig.
:h3.Using the ADC Without DMA
:p.We will use :pv.ADC1_IN6:epv. for our ADC input, which will mean our 
sequence length is equal to 1 and we will need to set PA1 to be analog 
mode. The following code provides an example of this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int waiting;
 
// turn on GPIO
RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_GPIOAEN;
 
// set PA1 to analog mode
GPIOA->MODER |= 0b1100;
 
// turn on the ADC
RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_ADCEN;
 
// disable deep power-down mode and wait for the ADC to initialize
ADC1->CR &= &tilde.ADC_CR_DEEPPWD;
for(waiting = 0; waiting < 5000; waiting++);
 
// turn on the regulator and wait for it to stabilize
ADC1->CR |= ADC_CR_ADVREGEN;
for(waiting = 0; waiting < 5000; waiting++);
 
// enable continuous conversion mode
ADC1->CFGR |= ADC_CFGR_CONT;
 
// set ADC1->DR even if we overran the ADC input voltage limit
ADC1->CFGR |= ADC_CFGR_OVRMOD;
 
// clear the sequence length bits, then set the length to 1 (0x00)
ADC1->SQR1 &= &tilde.(0x0F);
ADC1->SQR1 |= 0x00;
 
// clear the bits for input 1, and assign it to ADC1_IN6 (0x180)
ADC1->SQR1 &= &tilde.(0x7C0);
ADC1->SQR1 |= (0x180);
 
// enable the ADC and wait for it to become ready
ADC1->CR |= ADC_CR_ADEN;
while(!(ADC1->ISR & ADC_ISR_ADRDY));
 
// start conversion
ADC1->CR |= ADC_CR_ADSTART;
:exmp.
:figcap.ADC non-DMA setup example
:efig.
:p.Carefully cross-correlate this with the list of steps shown in the 
list under :hdref refid=adcstp.!
:p.In order to actually read the ADC value, simply read the following 
register at any time in your program (or perhaps in a timer ISR):
:xmp.ADC1->DR
:exmp.
:p.Remember, this is a 16-bit register that only has 12 significant 
bits; see :figref refid=adcpic. to see the effect of sampling a sine 
wave that oscillates around 1.65 volts.
:fn.Why 1.65 volts? Well, the sine wave in that figure was shifted up 
with a DC offset such that its modulation would span about 2.6 volts 
down to 0.7 volts!
:efn.
:h3 id=adcdma.Using ADC DMA Mode
:p.This is a modified version of the previous example that uses the 
first DMA controller's 0th stream to copy the ADC data register, 
:pk.ADC1->DR:epk., to a variable in our program that we can read at any 
time. This example is split into two code blocks:
:ol.
:li.DMA initialization code
:li.ADC initialization code
:eol.
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp keep=5.
uint16_t adc_buf;
 
// turn on DMA
RCC->AHB1ENR |= RCC_AHB1ENR_DMA1EN;
 
// set DMA1 channel 1 to ADC1
DMA1_CSELR->CSELR &= &tilde.DMA_CSELR_C1S;
 
// configure DMA1 channel 1 to do 16-bit transfers, increment
// the source (MINC) and destination (PINC) memory addresses as
// we go, turn on circular (CIRC) mode, and we want to transfer
// from the peripheral to the memory (so, DIR is 0)
DMA1_Channel1->CCR |= DMA_CCR_CIRC | DMA_CCR_MINC;
DMA1_Channel1->CCR &= &tilde.0b110000000000;
DMA1_Channel1->CCR |=  0b010000000000;       // this sets MSIZE
DMA1_Channel1->CCR &= &tilde.0b1100000000;
DMA1_Channel1->CCR |=  0b0100000000;         // this sets PSIZE
 
// set source and destination
DMA1_Channel1->CPAR = (uint32_t)&(ADC1->DR);
DMA1_Channel1->CMAR = (uint16_t)adc_buffer;  // re-typecast to 16-bit
 
// we want to transfer just one unsigned short at a time
DMA1_Channel1->CNDTR = 1;                    // one 16-bit item
:exmp.
:figcap.ADC + DMA setup example - DMA half
:efig.
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp keep=5.
int waiting;
 
// turn on GPIO
RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_GPIOAEN;
 
// set PA1 to analog mode
GPIOA->MODER |= 0b1100;
 
// power up ADC
RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_ADCEN;
 
// disable deep power-down mode and wait for the ADC to initialize
ADC1->CR &= &tilde.ADC_CR_DEEPPWD;
for(waiting = 0; waiting < 5000; waiting++);
 
// turn on the regulator and wait for it to stabilize
ADC1->CR |= ADC_CR_ADVREGEN;
for(waiting = 0; waiting < 5000; waiting++);
 
// enable continuous conversion mode
ADC1->CFGR |= ADC_CFGR_CONT;
 
// use DMA
ADC1->CFGR |= ADC_CFGR_DMAEN | ADC_CFGR_DMACFG;
 
// set ADC1->DR even if we overran the ADC input voltage limit
ADC1->CFGR |= ADC_CFGR_OVRMOD;
 
// clear the sequence length bits, then set the length to 1 (0x00)
ADC1->SQR1 &= &tilde.(0x0F);
ADC1->SQR1 |= 0x00;
 
// clear the bits for input 1, and assign it to ADC1_IN6 (0x180)
ADC1->SQR1 &= &tilde.(0x7C0);
ADC1->SQR1 |=  0x180;
 
// enable the ADC and wait for it to become ready
ADC1->CR |= ADC_CR_ADEN;
while(!(ADC1->ISR & ADC_ISR_ADRDY));
 
// start conversion
ADC1->CR |= ADC_CR_ADSTART;
:exmp.
:figcap.ADC + DMA setup example - ADC half 
:efig.
:p.Now, just like in the non-DMA example, you will have the ADC value 
crammed into the :pv.adc_buf:epv. buffer and only the first twelve bits 
will be significant!
:h1.Serial Communications 
:p.While none of this material is required in the ELEC 3040/3050 class, 
I am including this information in case you wish to use an STM32 in 
your Capstone project! 
:p.There are two serial interfaces that we will cover: 
:ol.
:li.:hp2.USART:ehp2. -- used for the commonplace :q.character 
displays:eq.,
:fn.These go by many names, but most of these feature 2 rows of 18 
characters; these are frequently used in Capstone projects! 
:efn.
communication with a computer, and more
:li.:hp2.SPI:ehp2. -- used for communication with serialized memory 
ICs, many types of sensors, and more
:eol.
:p.Let us learn how to configure the UART! 
:h2.USART 
:p.The :hp2.Universal Synchronous/Asynchronous 
Receiver/Transmitter,:ehp2. often called a :q.serial port,:eq. or a 
:q.COM port,:eq. 
:fn.Note that a COM port on the back of a PC or USB-to-serial adapter 
operates at :hp5.&pm.15 volts:ehp5. and will absolutely kill your STM32 
-- this UART connector type is called :hp2.RS232.:ehp2. 
:efn.
is a very common and simple way of (as discussed just above) 
communicating with PCs and input/output devices.
:i1.USART/UART 
:lblbox.USART or UART? 
:p.The STM32 UART controller has an :hp1.optional synchronous 
mode,:ehp1. wherein the controller provides an additional clock pin. 
:p.In asynchronous mode, you only use three pins: 
:ol.
:li.Ground 
:li.Receive 
:li.Transmit
:eol.
:p.Synchronous mode adds a :hp5.clock:ehp5. pin. 
:elblbox.
:h3.Computing the Baud Rate 
:p.Before you can send and receive anything, you have to determine what 
:hp2.baud rate:ehp2. you will be using! Here are some common baud 
rates: 
:table cols='1i'.
:tcap.Bauds
:row.
:c.300
:row.
:c.1200 
:row.
:c.2400 
:row.
:c.4800 
:row.
:c.9600 
:row.
:c.19200 
:row.
:c.38400 
:row.
:c.57600 
:row.
:c.115200 
:etable.
:p.For the following example, let's use :hp2.115200:ehp2. baud.
If our clock
:fn.This is :hp2.SYSCLK:ehp2. 
:efn.
defaults to 4 MHz, you can use the following formula to compute what 
the clock divider needs to be:  
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:df align=center.baud = <F sub CLK> over <divider>
:edf.
 
:figcap.USART clock divider formula
:efig.
:p.Simply algebraically rearrange the formula to solve for whichever 
value you need. So, if we enter 115200 baud as our baud rate and solve 
for the divider, we get a mantissa of 34 and a fraction of 72. 
:h3.Connecting the Pins 
:p.You will want to check the device datasheet (see 
:hdref refid=biblio.), and you will likely want to use :pv.USART1:epv.; 
as such, your transmit pin will be PA9 and your receive pin will be 
PA10. The alternate function for both of these will be AF7.
:fn.You will have to use the second indexing of the :pk.GPIOx->AFR:epk. 
register, so :pk.GPIOx->AFR&lbrk.1&rbrk.:epk..
:efn.
:h3.Send and Receive Functions 
:h3.Receive Interrupts 
:appendix.
:bibliog id=biblio.
:p.The following other books will be extensively useful in your studies:
:ul.
:li.:hp2.RM0394 Reference Manual:ehp2. -- for the following parts: 
STM32L41xxx, 42xxx, 43xxx, 44xxx, 45xxx, 46xxx
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.R0394 Reference manual.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
December 2024.
:li.:hp2.RM0090 Reference Manual:ehp2. -- for the following parts: 
STM32F405/415, STM32F407/417, STM32F427/437 and STM32F429/439
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.R0090 Reference manual.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
May 2026.
:li.:hp2.STM32L432KC Datasheet:ehp2.
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.STM32L432KB, STM32L432KC.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
May 2018.
:li.:hp2.STM32F411VE Datasheet:ehp2.
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.STM32F411xC, STM32F411xE.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
January 2024.
:li.:hp2.ELEC 2220 Textbook:ehp2.
:p.Zhu, Yifeng. :hp1.Embedded Systems with ARM Cortex-M in Assembly 
Language and C, 3rd Edition.:ehp1. E-Man Press, 2017.
:eul.
:h1 id=mxproj.Creating STM32CubeMX/IDE Projects
:p.Here is an outline of steps required to create an STM32 project.
:ol prefix='setup checkoff'.
:li.Create a directory
:fn.A :q.directory:eq. is a :hp5.folder:ehp5.; this term is more 
frequently heard amongst programmers!
:efn.
in one of the following locations:
:ul.
:li.The :pk.H:\:epk. drive
:li.A flash drive
:li.:hp3.NOT:ehp3. the root of the :pk.C:\:epk. drive!!
:eul.
:li.Open :hp2.STM32CubeMX:ehp2. from the Start menu.
:li.Click :rk.File:erk., then :rk.New Project...:erk.
:li.Several dialog boxes downloading files will appear, just let those 
run.
:li.In :q.Commercial Part Number:eq., enter the STM32 model:
:ul.
:li.:pk.STM32L432KCU6:epk., for the current 3040/3050 board (the 
:q.KC:eq. board)
:li.:pk.STM32L412KBU6:epk., for the older 3040/3050 board (the 
:q.KB:eq. board)
:li.:pk.STM32F411VET6:epk., for the 2200 board
:eul.
:li.Under the :pv.Part No:epv. header in the bottom half of the screen, 
click the part number that came up.
:li.Click :rk.Start Project:erk. at the top right.
:li.Click :rk.Project Manager:erk..
:li.In :hp2.Project Name:ehp2., enter a name of your choosing.
:li.In :hp2.Project Location:ehp2., click :rk.Browse:erk. and locate 
the directory you created in Step 1.
:note.If your path starts with something that looks like 
:pv.\\sage.eng.auburn.edu\:epv., you did not properly specify the 
directory you created.
:li.Make sure :hp2.Application Structure:ehp2. is set to 
:hp2.Advanced:ehp2..
:li.Change :hp2.Toolchain/IDE:ehp2. from :rk.EWARM:erk. 
to:rk.STM32CubeIDE:erk..
:li.Uncheck the checkbox to the left of :hp2.Use Default Firmware 
Location.:ehp2.
:li.In the :hp2.Firmware Relative Path:ehp2., click :rk.Browse:erk. and 
either type in or navigate to :pk.C:\Temp\STM32CubeFirmware:epk..
:note.If this step fails, re-check the box and continue to the next 
step; you'll have to wait a few minutes to download the firmware, 
though!
:li.Click :rk.Generate Code:erk. and wait for a while.
:li.Click :rk.Open Project:erk..
:li.STM32CubeIDE will open, permitting you to continue with the rest of 
your lab.
:eol.
:h1 id=fstring.Format Specifiers
:p.These are used in the :pk.printf:epk. and :pk.scanf:epk. family of C 
library functions; only :pk.scanf:epk. is available on the STM32 target 
C library in :pk.string.h:epk..
:table cols='1i 1i *'.
:tcap.Format Specifiers
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Specifier:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Type:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Description:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%d:epk. or :pk.%i:epk.
:c.:pk.int:epk.
:c.Signed decimal integer
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%u:epk.
:c.:pk.unsigned int:epk.
:c.Unsigned decimal integer
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%f:epk.
:c.:pk.float:epk.
:c.Decimal (floating-point)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%lf:epk.
:c.:pk.double:epk.
:c.Long decimal (floating-point)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%c:epk.
:c.:pk.char:epk.
:c.Single character
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%s:epk.
:c.:pk.char*:epk.
:c.Multiple characters (string)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%p:epk.
:c.:pk.void*:epk.
:c.Memory address as hexadecimal
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%x:epk. or :pk.%X:epk.
:c.:pk.int:epk.
:c.Unsigned hexadecimal number (:pk.%X:epk. is uppercase)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%o:epk.
:c.:pk.int:epk.
:c.Unsigned octal number
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%e:epk. or :pk.%E:epk.
:c.:pk.float/double:epk.
:c.Decimal in scientific notation
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.%%:epk.
:c.:hp1.n/a:ehp1.
:c.Print a literal % character
