:backm.
:glossary.
:p.Cross-references to other words that appear in the glossary are 
placed in :hp1.italic!:ehp1.
:gl.
:grpsep.A
:gt.Asynchronous
:gd.If an event is asynchronous, you can do other things while you wait 
for the event to complete. DMA is asynchronous.
:gt.ADC
:gd.Analog-to-Digital Converter. Samples an analog signal at specific 
times and converts it into a numeric representation. See 
:hdref refid=ADC. for more information!
:gt.AHB
:gd.Advanced High-performance Bus, the integrated data bus on the STM32 
that, like the :hp1.APB:ehp1., is hot-controllable.
:gt.APB
:gd.Advanced Peripheral Bus, the integrated bus on the STM32 that 
features peripherals that can be connected and disconnected from the 
CPU at will.
:gt.ARM
:gd.Advanced RISC Machine (originally Acorn RISC Machines, after the 
English computer company), the CPU architecture that the STM32 
implements.
:gt.ARR (Auto-reload register)
:gd.When you set the ARR register, a :hp1.counter:ehp1. will count up 
to this value and then generate an event. See :hdref refid=timers. for 
more information!
:grpsep.B
:gt.Baud rate 
:gd.The baud rate is the number of :hp1.bits per second:ehp1. 
transmitted on a serial link.
:gt.Bouncing
:gd.Unwanted jittering when a button is being pressed or released that 
may result in excessive interrupt generation or unstable control signal 
input.
:gt.Breakpoint
:gd.A specific memory address or line in a function that you wish for 
execution to stop on; these are implemented by the :hp1.debugger.:ehp1.
:grpsep.C
:gt.CAN
:gd.Controller Area Network. A multi-device bus-type network frequently 
used in automobiles and other such similar control systems.
:gt.Clock divider
:gd.A circuit (which, on the STM32, is configurable with 
the:pk.RCC:epk. register block) that divides the frequency of some 
master oscillator clock by some value to lower it.
:gt.Clock
:gd.A square-wave oscillator that clocks a sequential logic circuit, 
like a CPU.
:grpsep.D
:gt.DAC
:gd.Digital-to-Analog Converter. Takes a 12-bit decimal value and 
outputs a high-accuracy analog voltage.
:gt.Debounce
:gd.The act of removing multiple back-to-back button pressing events 
when a physical button is pressed (as the name implies, you have to 
remove "bouncing" from the button output signal)
:gt.Debugger
:gd.In the context of embedded systems, a debugger is a device that can 
stop and start the CPU, alter its memory, alter its flash, and possibly 
inspect CPU registers (and sometimes even peripheral registers).
:gt.Differential
:gd.If a signal is differential, it is carried on two wires; one 
carries positive values, and the other carries negative values. It is 
easier to interpret a signal that swings below ground level with 
differential signal pathways, and signals with a high chance of being 
lost in noise should always be carried differentially. See 
:hp1.single-ended.:ehp1.
:gt.DMA
:gd.Direct Memory Access. An additional component of the CPU can 
perform memory copying operations or peripheral driving operations 
asynchronously without the CPU intervening at all. The completion of a 
DMA event usually results in the generation of an interrupt.
:gt.Duty cycle
:gd.The percentage in which a square wave is turned "on", wherein a 50% 
duty cycle looks like a normal square wave.
:grpsep.E
:gt.EEPROM
:gd.Electronically-Erasable ROM, a block of memory on a microcontroller 
or discrete IC package that is intended to be written only a few times, 
but read far more times.
:gt.EXTI
:gd.External Interrupt. When a GPIO pin is allowed to flow to the CPU 
and generate an interrupt (by configuring the NVIC and EXTI register 
blocks), you are generating an EXTI event.
:grpsep.F
:gt.Flash
:gd.A type of :hp1.EEPROM:ehp1. that contains the stored program a 
microcontroller runs; some types of flash blocks on an STM32 can be 
used for user data.
:gt.Full-duplex
:gd.A serial interface that permits communication in both directions 
simultaneously. UART is full-duplex.
:grpsep.G
:gt.GPIO
:gd.General Purpose Input/Output, I/O pins that connect the 
microcontroller to the outside world.
:grpsep.H
:gt.Half-duplex
:gd.A serial interface that does not permit communication in both 
directions simultaneously. I&sup2.C is half-duplex.
:grpsep.I
:gt.Interrupt
:gd.A signal that pauses the CPU execution, saves the PC (program 
counter) register, runs a function, then restores the PC register and 
resumes normal execution. Interrupts are handled by ISRs.
:gt.I&sup2.C
:gd.Inter-Integrated Circuit, a low-speed serial device interface that 
requires only a clock and bidirectional data pin; this is a 
:hp1.half-duplex:ehp1. interface.
:gt.IRQ
:gd.Interrupt Request, an event that generates an interrupt.
:gt.ISR
:gd.Interrupt Service Routine, a function that the CPU jumps to 
whenever an interrupt fires.
:grpsep.L 
:gt.Level shifter 
:gd.This device converts the voltage levels of a serial communication 
interface, like RS232, to something palatable for a microcontroller's 
lower voltage levels.
:grpsep.N
:gt.NMI
:gd.Non-Maskable Interrupt, an interrupt that cannot be disabled and is 
usually triggered when the device malfunctions.
:gt.NVIC
:gd.Nested Vectored Interrupt Controller, the standard interrupt 
controller block found on :hp1.ARM Cortex-M:ehp1. series 
microcontroller CPUs.
:grpsep.P
:gt.Parallel 
:gd.Parallel communication involves sending all bits of a byte at the 
same time on at least 8 data pins at some specified :hp1.clock;:ehp1. 
the opposite of this is :hp1.serial:ehp1. resolution.
:gt.PC
:gd.Program Counter. This is the :hp1.register:ehp1. that holds the 
memory address of the currently-executing CPU instruction.
:gt.Prescaler
:gd.This is a type of :hp1.clock divider:ehp1. that controls the input 
clock frequency to a :hp1.timer.:ehp1.
:gt.PWM
:gd.Pulse-Width-Modulation. A simple way of getting a quasi-analog 
signal with a variable voltage from a bilevel (i.e. on or off) digital 
I/O pin by modulating the :hp1.duty cycle:ehp1. of the pin.
:grpsep.Q
:gt.Quantization
:gd.When you quantize a signal, you force it to certain pre-fixed 
values; this is similar to rounding wherein you might cut 3051.32 to 
3051 to allow a value to fit in a 12-bit register that can represent 
values ranging 0 to 4095.
:grpsep.R
:gt.RCC
:gd.Register and Clock Control, the control register that allows you to 
set the system clock source and other such things. This contains the 
:hp1.AHB:ehp1. and :hp1.APB:ehp1. control registers.
:gt.Resolution
:gd.The resolution of a sampled signal increases in accuracy with more 
bits; a formula that relates distortion, quantization loss, and bit 
depth to resolution can be written.
:gt.ROM
:gd.Read-Only Memory, a type of memory that usually contains the stored 
program a microcontroller or computer system runs.
:gt.Register
:gd.32-bit high-speed fields within the CPU that is the fundamental 
working storage for the CPU; see your notes from Computer Systems for 
more information.
:gt.RS232 
:gd.A physical serial port on a PC or terminal uses the RS232 
specification; the voltage levels switch between +15V and -15V to carry 
the data stream. You must use a :hp1.level shifter:ehp1. to connect 
this to a microcontroller.
:grpsep.S
:gt.Serial 
:gd.Serial communication involves sending each bit of a byte 
back-to-back at some pre-set :hp1.baud rate;:ehp1. the opposite of this 
is :hp1.parallel:ehp1. communication.
:gt.Single-ended
:gd.If a signal is single-ended, it is carried on one wire and is also 
more susceptible to noise. See :hp1.differential.:ehp1.
:gt.SPI
:gd.Serial Peripheral Interface. Many peripherals use SPI, ranging from 
ultrasonic range sensors, some microphones, RAM and ROM chips, SD 
cards, some character displays, and other devices of this nature.
:gt.ST-LINK
:gd.The :hp1.debugger:ehp1. included on STM32 development boards. If 
you are designing your own STM32-based board, you will need to either 
get an external ST-LINK box or add the chip directly onto your board.
:gt.STMicroelectronics
:gd.The company that made the STM32 microcontroller.
:gt.SVC
:gd.Supervisor Call, an interrupt that a user program will generate 
using a software interrupt generation CPU instruction that jumps into 
the operating system (the "supervisor") to handle a system call.
:gt.Synchronous
:gd.If an event is synchronous, you must wait for it to finish before 
you can move onto the next event.
:gt.SysTick
:gd.A special interrupt generated by an integral timer derived stably 
from the oscillator that provides the CPU clock. Used for the scheduler 
jiffy clock of an operating system or any number of tasks wherein you 
might need an event that fires repeatedly.
:grpsep.U
:gt.UART
:gd.Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter, the standard serial 
interface found on PCs and all manner of communication devices.
Sometimes, it may be :hp5.synchronous:ehp5., wherein it becomes a 
:hp2.USART:ehp2. (which is what the STM32 has).
:gt.USART
:gd.See UART.
:grpsep.V
:gt.vtable
:gd.A colloquial name for an array of function pointers.
:egl.
:index.
:euserdoc.
